WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.689 --> 00:00:06.180
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: Join me in welcoming
to Google, Jane Espenson.

00:00:06.180 --> 00:00:07.180
[applause]

00:00:07.180 --> 00:00:08.180
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: Thank you.

00:00:08.180 --> 00:00:09.180
This is fun.

00:00:09.180 --> 00:00:13.039
I like being here at Google.

00:00:13.039 --> 00:00:14.759
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: OK, I'm gonna take you
back.

00:00:14.759 --> 00:00:15.759
Back.

00:00:15.759 --> 00:00:16.759
[laughter]

00:00:16.759 --> 00:00:17.759
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: Doodoodoodoo.

00:00:17.759 --> 00:00:18.759
It's all blurry.

00:00:18.759 --> 00:00:19.759
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: Pre 1992.

00:00:19.759 --> 00:00:20.759
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: Oh no, OK.

00:00:20.759 --> 00:00:21.759
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: So what were you doing
then?

00:00:21.759 --> 00:00:22.759
You were in linguistics.

00:00:22.759 --> 00:00:23.759
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: I was in grad school.

00:00:23.759 --> 00:00:24.759
I was in college from '82 to '92.

00:00:24.759 --> 00:00:25.759
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: Right.

00:00:25.759 --> 00:00:26.759
[laughs]

00:00:26.759 --> 00:00:30.510
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: You've hit the archaeological
level that is my college years.

00:00:30.510 --> 00:00:31.900
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: And what were you working
on there?

00:00:31.900 --> 00:00:33.830
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: I was working on cognitive
science.

00:00:33.830 --> 00:00:39.500
So, I started in computer science added linguistics
as a double major as an undergrad and then

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:43.750
realized, "Hey, linguistics plus computer
science equals cognitive science," which you

00:00:43.750 --> 00:00:46.579
can tell isn't a science because it has the
word science in it.

00:00:46.579 --> 00:00:47.579
[laughter]

00:00:47.579 --> 00:00:50.899
And spent five years doing that in grad school
with George Lakoff.

00:00:50.899 --> 00:00:52.229
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: OK.

00:00:52.229 --> 00:00:55.480
So, you went to reality and became a writer.

00:00:55.480 --> 00:01:01.889
So, is there anything about your past like,
'82 to '92 about conceptualization of causation

00:01:01.889 --> 00:01:04.290
and metaphors that has informed your work?

00:01:04.290 --> 00:01:07.560
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: I ask myself about that.

00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:10.060
For one thing, I needed those years to grow
up.

00:01:10.060 --> 00:01:15.750
So, my pseudo-maturity is a result of those
years.

00:01:15.750 --> 00:01:21.690
But certainly, the stuff that I like to write
has a metaphorical layer in it.

00:01:21.690 --> 00:01:22.690
I don't--.

00:01:22.690 --> 00:01:25.810
I'm not particularly interested in writing
household drama.

00:01:25.810 --> 00:01:26.880
I like writing sci-fi.

00:01:26.880 --> 00:01:31.340
When I write household drama, I like it to
be something like the show "Dinosaurs" that

00:01:31.340 --> 00:01:36.770
I worked on, where it's like it's a normal
American household but they're dinosaurs.

00:01:36.770 --> 00:01:38.540
[laughter]

00:01:38.540 --> 00:01:42.940
I find it allows you to speak more honestly
about what's going on in the world.

00:01:42.940 --> 00:01:49.250
So, the events on "Battlestar Galactica" could
have taken place on an ordinary aircraft carrier

00:01:49.250 --> 00:01:56.190
on water, but it's much more exciting that
it's an aircraft carrier out in space, in

00:01:56.190 --> 00:01:57.190
space.

00:01:57.190 --> 00:01:58.190
[laughter]

00:01:58.190 --> 00:02:02.560
You can speak about both those shows, Dinosaurs
and "Battlestar Galactica" took on middle

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:07.600
eastern wars as a topic in a way that a show
wouldn't be allowed to if it was like we're

00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:08.910
going to do a show about U.S. soldiers.

00:02:08.910 --> 00:02:13.730
So we could switch around who was being the
bad guy in any particular episode.

00:02:13.730 --> 00:02:20.410
We could move the morality around a bit or
remove it entirely without there being real

00:02:20.410 --> 00:02:23.910
world implications we could expose the real
world.

00:02:23.910 --> 00:02:29.870
And so, the fact that I like that metaphorical
layer, it's probably not so much that grad

00:02:29.870 --> 00:02:35.220
school supplied me with that interest, but
that they were both caused by the same initial

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:36.220
interest in it.

00:02:36.220 --> 00:02:39.970
I like the idea of how do we really understand
things.

00:02:39.970 --> 00:02:43.840
How do we filter things so that we can grapple
with them?

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:48.340
And that led me both to grad school and to
my interest in sci-fi.

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:50.810
Certainly, my interest in sci-fi predated
grad school.

00:02:50.810 --> 00:02:55.580
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: So now, I'm skipping
a question because you're bringing up the

00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:56.580
moral cheat sheet.

00:02:56.580 --> 00:02:57.580
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: Yes.

00:02:57.580 --> 00:02:58.580
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: And I love that expression.

00:02:58.580 --> 00:03:00.110
Not having it in other words.

00:03:00.110 --> 00:03:02.410
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: Yeah.

00:03:02.410 --> 00:03:06.209
This is an idea I had when I went in to speak--.

00:03:06.209 --> 00:03:10.280
When you get hired on show they don't just
look at your writing samples and say, "OK.

00:03:10.280 --> 00:03:11.280
Show up Monday."

00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:15.820
You also have to come in and meet with the
show runner and sometimes that meeting is

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:17.320
very perfunctory.

00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:18.690
They know they like your writing.

00:03:18.690 --> 00:03:20.370
They know they're inclined to hire you.

00:03:20.370 --> 00:03:23.270
They just want to make sure that you're someone
they can stand being in a room with--that

00:03:23.270 --> 00:03:24.270
you're not crazy.

00:03:24.270 --> 00:03:27.150
So, I call this the "wear pants" meeting.

00:03:27.150 --> 00:03:28.150
[laughter]

00:03:28.150 --> 00:03:30.950
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: If you show up wearing pants
then you're probably OK because they already

00:03:30.950 --> 00:03:31.950
like you.

00:03:31.950 --> 00:03:33.450
But sometimes you wanna--.

00:03:33.450 --> 00:03:38.530
If you really want the job, you wanna go in
armed with some insight about their show.

00:03:38.530 --> 00:03:43.020
So, what I came in with at "Battlestar" was
that I admired that it had no moral cheat

00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:44.020
sheet.

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:48.090
And Ron, the show runner, leans so far out
in his chair in excitement, I thought he was

00:03:48.090 --> 00:03:49.090
going to fall on the floor.

00:03:49.090 --> 00:03:51.780
I was like "OK good, I hit something."

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:53.591
Yeah, because that's exactly what he had been
going for.

00:03:53.591 --> 00:03:58.070
For so many shows you know that your hero's
not going to make a bad choice, not going

00:03:58.070 --> 00:03:59.560
to make an immoral choice.

00:03:59.560 --> 00:04:02.849
On "Star Trek", for example, this was always
the way.

00:04:02.849 --> 00:04:08.480
So, if Picard was advocating this, unless
he'd been body switched you knew that it was

00:04:08.480 --> 00:04:09.709
the right thing to do.

00:04:09.709 --> 00:04:12.770
So you could as a viewer sit back and go,
"OK good.

00:04:12.770 --> 00:04:13.770
He's doing the right thing."

00:04:13.770 --> 00:04:15.950
You didn't have to think about the choice.

00:04:15.950 --> 00:04:21.150
Ron came out of the "Star Trek" world and
then created "Battlestar."

00:04:21.150 --> 00:04:25.820
And I think it was very much a reaction in
his mind that he wanted to tell stories with

00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:29.230
shades of gray that weren't so clear-cut.

00:04:29.230 --> 00:04:33.480
And he really loved that I picked up on the
fact that even though we love and respect

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:40.290
President Roslin, we love and respect Admiral
Adama, doesn't mean they're always right.

00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:43.480
You don't have a moral cheat sheet to go,
"Oh, who's making the argument?

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:44.480
Adama?

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:45.480
OK.

00:04:45.480 --> 00:04:46.480
That's the right thing to do."

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:47.480
He did--.

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:49.000
Made wrong decisions, immoral decisions all
the time.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:51.000
Sometimes, they were right and immoral.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:53.270
Sometimes, they were wrong and immoral.

00:04:53.270 --> 00:04:56.650
But you had no way of knowing which one it
was going into the argument.

00:04:56.650 --> 00:05:01.680
And often, both sides had their merits and
you just had to go, "Which would I do?"

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:02.680
And it was--.

00:05:02.680 --> 00:05:06.440
It makes for a much more involving and participatory
show.

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:12.300
And I've thought a lot about what makes a
cult hit, what makes a show with a fandom

00:05:12.300 --> 00:05:19.270
where, where the fans are so passionate about
a show that they consider themselves a community.

00:05:19.270 --> 00:05:23.630
A lot of that has to do with the degree that
they are engaged with the show.

00:05:23.630 --> 00:05:26.370
The amount where it feels participatory for
them.

00:05:26.370 --> 00:05:31.311
In an argument in which they are not, being
told passively which side to be on but they

00:05:31.311 --> 00:05:35.250
have to actively engage and think about what
side they'd be on.

00:05:35.250 --> 00:05:42.020
That's one of the ingredients in the recipe
for cult stardom and "Battlestar's" certainly

00:05:42.020 --> 00:05:43.020
achieved that.

00:05:43.020 --> 00:05:44.140
I think that's a big part of why.

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:45.880
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: OK.

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:48.840
So, you prefer writing for TV as opposed to--.

00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:49.840
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: Oh, yes.

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:50.840
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: OK.

00:05:50.840 --> 00:05:51.840
Why?

00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:52.840
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: Oh my god.

00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:53.840
Movies are awful.

00:05:53.840 --> 00:05:57.010
[laughter]
They--.

00:05:57.010 --> 00:05:58.990
In TV, we're the boss.

00:05:58.990 --> 00:06:01.610
In movies, directors are the boss.

00:06:01.610 --> 00:06:04.770
Now that Joss Whedon has gone to movies, what's
he doing?

00:06:04.770 --> 00:06:06.980
He's writing and directing.

00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:10.500
Because otherwise you are not even on the
set.

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:18.850
Your script is the launching point for visionaries
to come in and imagine a world and the writers

00:06:18.850 --> 00:06:22.190
work is done on most movies.

00:06:22.190 --> 00:06:23.190
I don't care for that.

00:06:23.190 --> 00:06:27.160
On TV, we're the bosses, we create the world,
we make the decisions.

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:31.259
A director is hired week by week, they come
in, sometimes they're fantastic sometimes

00:06:31.259 --> 00:06:32.419
they are very visionary.

00:06:32.419 --> 00:06:36.080
Sometimes they come back a lot and they become
part of the fabric of the show.

00:06:36.080 --> 00:06:40.640
But a lot of times, it's just a guy that comes
in for a week and he has to do what we say.

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:43.990
And if we don't think he's doing it right,
we can fire him.

00:06:43.990 --> 00:06:44.990
We have the power.

00:06:44.990 --> 00:06:47.000
We sit there on the set.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.259
Technically, if I want to give a note to an
actor, I'm supposed to tell the director and

00:06:51.259 --> 00:06:52.480
the director gives that note.

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:56.280
But usually we're sitting in a chair just
like this and I look over and there's an actor

00:06:56.280 --> 00:06:58.979
right here saying, "How should I say this?

00:06:58.979 --> 00:07:01.050
What did you mean by this or can I do this?"

00:07:01.050 --> 00:07:02.919
And I'm just giving them direct instructions.

00:07:02.919 --> 00:07:05.370
You'd never have that on a feature set.

00:07:05.370 --> 00:07:09.070
Also, features never have to get made.

00:07:09.070 --> 00:07:13.360
There's no machine demanding that, "Well,
we've got a time slot.

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:15.910
You said September third; we gotta put it
on the air.

00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:17.170
We gotta send it out."

00:07:17.170 --> 00:07:19.750
Then stuff gets shoved it gets moved, they
make new decisions.

00:07:19.750 --> 00:07:22.020
A new head of studio comes in all those things
are sidelined.

00:07:22.020 --> 00:07:24.650
Cabin in the Woods has been done for years.

00:07:24.650 --> 00:07:26.301
You know, Joss's amazing new movie.

00:07:26.301 --> 00:07:28.550
And it's coming out now.

00:07:28.550 --> 00:07:33.050
Luckily it is still fresh as a freshly cut
thing.

00:07:33.050 --> 00:07:34.330
[laughter]

00:07:34.330 --> 00:07:35.330
Because it's amazing.

00:07:35.330 --> 00:07:38.539
It doesn't show the delay but delays happen.

00:07:38.539 --> 00:07:42.979
TV is a monster that eats every week, you
need to get stuff on the air.

00:07:42.979 --> 00:07:46.720
So I have had six episodes in the last year.

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:50.979
I had six episodes of "Once Upon A Time".

00:07:50.979 --> 00:07:51.979
Eleven episodes of "Husbands."

00:07:51.979 --> 00:07:57.470
My "Game of Thrones", I guess, was in this
last year.

00:07:57.470 --> 00:07:58.470
Just--.

00:07:58.470 --> 00:08:01.229
And some other stuff I wrote that hasn't aired
yet for secret projects.

00:08:01.229 --> 00:08:08.250
Or you could end up with something ten episodes
eleven, whatever, a year.

00:08:08.250 --> 00:08:12.120
Whereas a feature writer can go four years
working on a project and nothing hits the

00:08:12.120 --> 00:08:14.620
screen and maybe never will.

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:16.319
Nonsense.

00:08:16.319 --> 00:08:17.330
Come to TV.

00:08:17.330 --> 00:08:18.330
[laughter]

00:08:18.330 --> 00:08:20.770
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: So you mention "Game of
Thrones."

00:08:20.770 --> 00:08:21.770
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: Yeah

00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:25.090
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: And the scene to me that
is the most horrific is that golden crown.

00:08:25.090 --> 00:08:26.840
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: Oooo [laughs]

00:08:26.840 --> 00:08:27.840
[laughter]

00:08:27.840 --> 00:08:30.900
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And you mentioned in one
of the interviews I watched-- I watched many

00:08:30.900 --> 00:08:34.690
this weekend-- that you don't write in sequence
necessarily.

00:08:34.690 --> 00:08:36.270
Can you talk about that?

00:08:36.270 --> 00:08:37.270
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: Yeah.

00:08:37.270 --> 00:08:43.159
I find that I wanna write the scenes that
I can most strongly visualize first.

00:08:43.159 --> 00:08:47.890
And these are usually two person emotional
scenes in which people are sitting down and

00:08:47.890 --> 00:08:48.890
talking.

00:08:48.890 --> 00:08:50.110
And every script's got some of those.

00:08:50.110 --> 00:08:56.399
And they usually are the scenes that make
you cry, that make you feel, and they are

00:08:56.399 --> 00:08:57.399
delicate little scenes.

00:08:57.399 --> 00:09:01.680
But they are also often the ones you have
most clearly in your head when you sit down

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:04.050
to work.

00:09:04.050 --> 00:09:05.050
And you're not--.

00:09:05.050 --> 00:09:10.220
You don't have a lot of considerations in
your mind other than pulling the emotion out.

00:09:10.220 --> 00:09:13.330
You're not worried about the geography and
who spoke last.

00:09:13.330 --> 00:09:17.370
"Is that person been standing silent in the
corner for two pages?"

00:09:17.370 --> 00:09:18.370
Like they're--.

00:09:18.370 --> 00:09:20.270
I tend to go to those first.

00:09:20.270 --> 00:09:24.130
And those tend to give you a pretty good place
to aim at.

00:09:24.130 --> 00:09:27.860
Like, you've gotta get the characters to the
emotional states such that they can have that

00:09:27.860 --> 00:09:30.350
heart to heart talk.

00:09:30.350 --> 00:09:38.040
The last scenes I tend to write are action
and great big group scenes where you've got

00:09:38.040 --> 00:09:39.170
seven people in the scene.

00:09:39.170 --> 00:09:40.740
Just because there are so many moving parts.

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:43.550
There is so much architecture to figure out.

00:09:43.550 --> 00:09:45.010
Like--.

00:09:45.010 --> 00:09:47.430
And they're often procedurally scenes.

00:09:47.430 --> 00:09:52.920
All you need to know about the fight is who
won because that's what drives you into the

00:09:52.920 --> 00:09:53.920
next scene.

00:09:53.920 --> 00:09:55.110
So, you can kind of skip that for now.

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:57.899
"Oh, there's a fight and Buffy will win it."

00:09:57.899 --> 00:09:58.899
[laughter]

00:09:58.899 --> 00:10:02.320
I'll go back later and figure out what she
stabs him with.

00:10:02.320 --> 00:10:03.320
[laughs]

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:04.320
[laughter]

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:08.330
But I'm not going to waste brainpower on that
right now when I've still got the big emotional

00:10:08.330 --> 00:10:09.330
moment to write.

00:10:09.330 --> 00:10:10.820
So, I tend to write out of order.

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:12.070
A lot of authors don't.

00:10:12.070 --> 00:10:15.440
A lot of TV writers just go front to back.

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:20.140
On "Game of Thrones", that was totally weird
because it was pre-existing material.

00:10:20.140 --> 00:10:22.060
It was an adaptation.

00:10:22.060 --> 00:10:27.310
So, I was literally told, the scene, your
episode will go from this page number to that

00:10:27.310 --> 00:10:28.310
page number.

00:10:28.310 --> 00:10:32.920
So, the first thing I did was go to the book,
look at the scenes, transcribe George R.R

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:36.180
Martin's dialogue and start messing with it
from there.

00:10:36.180 --> 00:10:40.500
Because you know the amount of scene that's,
the amount of dialogue that's in one of his

00:10:40.500 --> 00:10:46.140
scenes could fill ten pages and it needs to
fill two and a half for the scene.

00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:49.130
So, you've gotta pick and choose.

00:10:49.130 --> 00:10:53.240
So, there's a lot of work to be done but the--.

00:10:53.240 --> 00:10:56.180
All those pivot points, all those big things
are there.

00:10:56.180 --> 00:11:00.580
In a certain sense, everything is equal importance
when someone has already done the heavy lifting

00:11:00.580 --> 00:11:03.280
and working out the heartbreak.

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:07.120
So that, I think, I really wrote that one
less out of order than anything I've ever

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:10.650
written because the plowing of the field had
been done.

00:11:10.650 --> 00:11:12.570
I was just going along planting in the furrows.

00:11:12.570 --> 00:11:13.570
[laughter]

00:11:13.570 --> 00:11:14.690
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Remember that one.

00:11:14.690 --> 00:11:15.690
[laughter]

00:11:15.690 --> 00:11:17.380
&gt;&gt;Jane Espenson: I just thought of that.

00:11:17.380 --> 00:11:18.610
That's pretty good.

00:11:18.610 --> 00:11:19.610
[laughter]

00:11:19.610 --> 00:11:22.300
&gt;&gt; Female Presenter: Well, Spike was one of
my favorite characters.

00:11:22.300 --> 00:11:25.690
Buffy and I like Rumpelstiltskin now, too
a lot.

00:11:25.690 --> 00:11:26.720
Do you have characters?

00:11:26.720 --> 00:11:28.709
Someone you like writing for?

00:11:28.709 --> 00:11:30.370
&gt;&gt; Jane Espenson: Yeah.

00:11:30.370 --> 00:11:33.470
Rumple has been amazing because can't go too
far.

00:11:33.470 --> 00:11:39.550
I've never dealt with a character who is so
gloriously over the top.

00:11:39.550 --> 00:11:41.750
Spike was amazing to write for.

00:11:41.750 --> 00:11:42.750
The--.

00:11:42.750 --> 00:11:49.400
Even though I don't in real life like bad
boys, they're fun to write for.

00:11:49.400 --> 00:11:52.959
Anya I loved writing for because she's so
blunt.

00:11:52.959 --> 00:11:57.800
And in a way, she was super easy 'cause you
just had to write what she was thinking, or

00:11:57.800 --> 00:11:58.940
to say what she was thinking.

